Compile the ffmpeg-sys-next `check.c` version-detection probe for the
target architecture instead of forcing it to host arch.

Upstream (zmwangx/rust-ffmpeg-sys 8.1.0) hard-codes
`.target(&env::var("HOST").unwrap())` so the runtime probe binary can
execute on the build host. This breaks cross-compilation on Linux:
the probe is fed target-arch headers from pkg-config (e.g. arm64
`/usr/include/aarch64-linux-gnu/libavutil/...`) but compiled by the
host x86_64 clang, which chokes on aarch64-only attributes such as
`__neon_vector_type__` and `__SVFloat32_t` in glibc 2.39's
`<bits/math-vector.h>`.

The fix is one line: compile the probe for the target arch. The
resulting target-arch ELF is then executed by the build script as
usual; on Linux hosts with `qemu-user-static` + `binfmt_misc`
registered (Ubuntu's `qemu-user-static` apt package does this on
install via dpkg postinst hooks) the kernel routes the foreign-arch
binary through QEMU emulation transparently. Rollio's
`make deps TARGET_ARCH=arm64` recipe pulls the qemu apt packages so
this is guaranteed available whenever the cross build is being run.

Patched into the vendored submodule by `make apply-vendored-patches`
(invoked transitively by `rust-build` / `rust-test` / `rust-lint`).
Idempotent: skipped if the patched marker is already present.

--- a/build.rs
+++ b/build.rs
@@ -788,8 +788,12 @@ fn check_features(
     .expect("Write failed");

     let executable = out_dir.join(if cfg!(windows) { "check.exe" } else { "check" });
+    // Cross-compile the probe for the target arch. The resulting binary is
+    // executed below; on Linux hosts with qemu-user-static + binfmt_misc
+    // registered, foreign-arch binaries run transparently via QEMU emulation
+    // (see Rollio's `make deps TARGET_ARCH=<arch>` recipe).
     let mut compiler = cc::Build::new()
-        .target(&env::var("HOST").unwrap()) // don't cross-compile this
+        .target(&env::var("TARGET").unwrap())
         .get_compiler()
         .to_command();
